The theory has two main components: special relativity and general relativity.  Special relativity postulates that the laws of physics are the same for all observers in uniform motion relative to each other. This theory challenged the traditional notion of absolute time and space, introducing the concept of spacetime as a unified fabric. Key predictions include time dilation (time appears to pass slower for an observer in motion) and length contraction (objects appear shorter when viewed from a moving reference frame).  General relativity builds upon special relativity by incorporating gravity as a curvature of spacetime caused by massive objects.
